	# A thought on Static Mockups 
	 The other day as I was going through my old computer, I found one of the many mockups I did for a project. More than three years has passed, the design still holds up well. I stared at the nice typography for a minute and thought, how come I didn&rsquo;t ship it?  
	
	<figure>
		<img src="assets/img/fraction-matter.jpg">
		<figcaption>
			One of the many concepts I had for Curate.it, my thesis project for school. Photo credit to from top down: <a href="http://www.markpeckmezian.com/">Mark Peckmezian</a>, <a href="http://silasdominey.tumblr.com/">Silas Dominey</a>, <a href="http://www.glenerler.com/">Glen Erler</a>, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walker_Evans">Walker Evans</a>
		</figcaption>
	</figure>

	I looked through folders of discarded static mockups. I was too busy worrying about my work not being good enough. Remember the [Imposter Syndrome article](https://medium.com/@aliciatweet/overcoming-impostor-syndrome-bdae04e46ec5) you read some time ago? Exactly that, or very similar. 

	I kept on starting from scratch over and over again. Each time I couldn&rsquo;t make up my mind. I was afraid to make the wrong decison. &ldquo;You think too much&rdquo;, as my hair dresser always told me in our therapy a.k.a hair cutting session. I wanted everything to be perfect the first time around.

	Start small. Do it right away when you think of an idea, when you are still excited about it. Don&rsquo;t take too long. First time you make something, there will be flaws. Prioritize. Iterate. Be disciplined. Get yourself into a momentum. 

	More importantly, have fun with whatever you do. Eventually you will ship the project you are proud of.

